item.label: Commissure, Corpus callosum
item.name: Commissure, Corpus callosum
item.description: The corpus callosum is a massive curved commissure that interconnects corresponding areas of the two cerebral hemispheres so that these areas may function in a coordinated manner.

item.label: Fornix
item.name: Fornix
item.description: The fornix is a compact bundle of axons, primarily efferents from the hippocampus to the ipsilateral septal nuclei and hypothalamus. Parts of the fornix from the hippocampus and beyond are the fimbria, crus, body and column.

item.label: Internal capsule, Posterior limb
item.name: Internal capsule, Posterior limb
item.description: The posterior limb of the internal capsule is located between the lentiform nucleus laterally and the thalamus medially. It includes connections between the ventral anterior (VA), ventral lateral (VL), ventral posterior nuclei (VPL/VPM) of thalamus with the motor, somatosensory and other areas of parietal cerebral cortex as well as corticospinal and corticobulbar fibers. A portion of the posterior limb passes beneath the lentiform nucleus (sublenticular); it includes the auditory radiation from the medial geniculate nucleus of thalamus to the temporal lobe of the cerebral cortex and a portion of the optic radiation from the lateral geniculate nucleus to the occipital cerebral cortex. A portion of the posterior limb passes posterior to the lentiform nucleus (retrolenticular); it includes a major portion of the optic radiation from the lateral geniculate nucleus to occipital cerebral cortex plus connections between the thalamus (pulvinar and lateral posterior nuclei) and the parietal-occipital-temporal association cortex.

item.label: Corpus striatum, Caudate nucleus
item.name: Corpus striatum, Caudate nucleus
item.description: The caudate nucleus is the medial portion of the striatum. It consists of a large head that bulges into the anterior horn of the lateral ventricle, a body that narrows and curves along the body of the lateral ventricle and a tail that continues through the atrium or trigone of the lateral ventricle and into the inferior horn of the lateral ventricle. Principal connections are with the prefrontal and other association areas of cerebral cortex.

item.label: Diencephalon
item.name: Diencephalon
item.description: Developmentally, the diencephalon and telencephalon are derived from the most anterior aspect of the developing neural tube, i.e. the prosencephalon. It includes the thalamus, hypothalamus, epithalamus and subthalamus. The retina, optic nerve and tract and neurohypophysis are also considered to be part of the diencephalon since they are formed as outgrowths from the diencephalon.

item.label: Epithalamus
item.name: Epithalamus
item.description: The epithalamus is one of the four divisions of the diencephalon, it includes the habenular nuclei and the pineal gland.

item.label: Habenular commissure
item.name: Habenular commissure
item.description: The habenular commissure is a band of commissural nerve fibers located rostral to the pineal gland.  It connects the habenular nuclei across the midline and thus contributes to the habenular trigone.

item.label: Habenular nucleus
item.name: Habenular nucleus
item.description: The habenular nuclei are small nuclei located on the dorsomedial aspect of the caudal thalamus. They receive afferents from septal nuclei, preoptic area, etc. via the stria medullaris of the thalamus and send efferents to reticular nuclei of the midbrain via the habenulointerpeduncular tracdt. They are part of limbic system circuits but their function is unclear.

item.label: Pineal gland
item.name: Pineal gland
item.description: The pineal gland is the part of the epithalamus that extends caudally from the area of the habenular nuclei and into the superior cistern, immediately dorsal to the superior colliculi. As an endocrine gland, it secretes melatonin and is involved with circadian rhythms and the sleep-wake cycle.

item.label: Posterior commissure
item.name: Posterior commissure
item.description: The posterior commissure consists of nerve fibers that interconnect the two sides of the rostral midbrain and pretectum. These fibers are involved in the consensual aspect of the pupillary light reflex and in coordinating vertical eye movements.

item.label: Thalamus
item.name: Thalamus
item.description: The thalamus is a large collection of nuclei that have major connections with the cerebral cortex involving both sensory and motor functions. Some thalamic nuclei have very specific connections relative to visual, auditory and somatosensory afferents and their projection to specific areas of cerebral cortex, while other nuclei have more general inputs and connections with association areas of cerebral cortex.

item.label: External medullary lamina
item.name: External medullalry lamina
item.description: The external medullary lamina of the thalamus is a thin layer of nerve fibers located lateral to the thalamus and medial to the reticular nucleus of the thalamus and posterior limb of the internal capsule. Note: Do not confuse with the external medullary lamina that is located between the globus pallidus and putamen.

item.label: Medical geniculate nucleus
item.name: Medical geniculate nucleus
item.description: The medial geniculate thalamic nucleus (MGN) deals with hearing.  It receives input from the cochlea via the cochlear nuclei, lateral lemniscus and inferior colliculus. It projects to primary auditory cortex in the temporal lobe (transverse temporal or Heschl's gyri) via the sublenticular part of the internal capsule.

item.label: Lateral geniculate nucleus
item.name: Lateral geniculate nucleus
item.description: The lateral geniculate thalamic nucleus (LGN) deals with vision.  It receives input from the retina via the optic nerve and tract. It projects to the primary visual cortex in the occipital lobe (cuneus and lingual gyri) via the geniculocalcarine tract.  The geniculocalcarine tract is AKA the optic radiation and travels in both the sublenticular and retrolentricular portions of the internal capsule.

item.label: Visual pathway, Optic tract
item.name: Visual pathway, Optic tract
item.description: The Optic tract consists of optic nerve axons that serve the contralateral visual field.  These axons originate in the ipsilateral temporal retina and contralateral nasal retina and terminate in the lateral geniculate nucleus as well as the pretectal area.

item.label: Pulvinar
item.name: Pulvinar
item.description: The pulvinar is the largest of the thalamic nuclei. It has connections with parietal-occipital-temporal association cerebral cortex.

item.label: Reticular nucleus
item.name: Reticular nucleus
item.description: The reticular nucleus of the thalamus is a thin shell of neurons surrounding the ventral and lateral aspect of the thalamus. It is sandwiched between the internal capsule and the external medullary lamina of the thalamus. It has no projections to cerebral cortex. It receives afferents from the thalamus and cerebral cortex and sends GABAergic efferents back to the thalamus.

item.label: Midbrain
item.name: Midbrain
item.description: The midbrain is AKA the mesencephalon. Within its parts (tectum, tegmentum, substantia nigra and cerebral crus or basis pedunculi), it contains cranial nerve nuclei, all of the clinically important ascending and descending tracts, etc. It is traversed by the cerebral aqueduct or aqueduct of Sylvius. It originates developmentally from the mesencephalon.

item.label: Midbrain, tegmentum
item.name: Midbrain, tegmentum
item.description: The tegmentum is that portion of the midbrain that lies between the cerebral aqueduct and the crus cerebri.  It includes the major ascending sensory tracts (medial lemniscus, spinothalamic), the red nucleus and the substantia nigra.

item.label: Periaqueductal gray matter
item.name: Periaqueductal gray matter
item.description: Periaqueductal gray matter is the area of gray matter surrounding the cerebral aqueduct of the midbrain. Some of the neurons in this area are part of a descending analgesic pathway that relays in the nucleus raphe magnus of the medulla and subsequently blocks pain at the level of the dorsal horn.

item.label: Oculomotor nucleus
item.name: Oculomotor nuclei
item.description: This third or oculomotor cranial nerve nucleus is located in the midline of the midbrain at the level of the superior colliculi. It consists of lower motor neurons that innervate the medial rectus, superior rectus, inferior rectus, inferior oblique and levator palpebrae muscles that move the eye. It also contains pre-ganglionic parasympathetic neurons in a part of the nuclear complex called the Edinger-Westphal nucleus. These parasympathetic fibers terminate in the ciliary ganglion; post-ganglionic fibers from the ciliary ganglion innervate the constrictors of the pupil and the ciliary muscles.

item.label: Medial longitudinal fasciculus
item.name: Medial longitudinal fasciculus
item.description: The medial longitudinal fasciculus is an important ascending fiber bundle involved in the coordination of horizontal eye movements through its origin in the vestibular nuclei and termination in the oculomotor and abducens nuclei. It is an important component of the VOR (vestibulo-ocular) reflex. A descending component of this tract (AKA medial vestibulospinal tract) travels to cervical levels of the cord and is involved in turning of the head in response to vestibular stimulation.

item.label: Inferior colliculus, brachium
item.name: Inferior colliculus, brachium
item.description: The brachium of the inferior colliculus is AKA the inferior brachium. It is a band of nerve fibers carrying auditory input from the inferior colliculus of the midbrain to the medial geniculate nucleus of the thalamus. It is clearly visible grossly on the lateral aspect of the midbrain.

item.label: Somatosensory tracts
item.name: Somatosensory tracts
item.description: The somatosensory tracts include the dorsal column-medial lemniscal, spinothalamic and trigeminothalamic.  They terminate in the ventral posterior nucleus of the thalamus after traveling through the brain stem.

item.label: Red nucleus
item.name: Red nucleus
item.description: The red nucleus is a large, round nucleus in the tegmentum of the midbrain that appears pink or red on freshly-sectioned tissue. It is involved with motor control via its connections with the cerebellum. It receives contralateral input from both the dentate and interposed deep cerebellar nuclei; its primary output in the human is to the ipsilateral inferior olivary nucleus via the central tegmental tract. Since the inferior olivary nucleus projects to contralateral cerebellum, the red nucleus is part of a feedback loop to the cerebellum. While the red nucleus gives origin to a significant rubrospinal tract in non-human species, this tract appears to be of limited extent and importance in humans.

item.label: Central tegmental tract
item.name: Central tegmental tract
item.description: The central tegmental tract is a large, heterogeneous tract traveling through the central or tegmental portion of the brainstem. It includes descending fibers from the red nucleus to the ipsilateral inferior olivary nucleus, ascending taste fibers from the rostral solitary nucleus as well as multiple inputs and outputs of the reticular formation.

item.label: Cerebello-rubro-thalamic tract
item.name: Cerebello-rubro-thalamic tract
item.description: The cerebello-rubro-thalamic tract originates in the dentate and interpositus nuclei of the cerebellum, travels through the superior cerebellar peduncle and terminates in the red nucleus and the ventral lateral nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Substantia nigra
item.name: Substantia nigra
item.description: The substantia nigra is a large band-like nucleus in the midbrain located between the crus cerebri and the red nuclei of the tegmentum. It has two parts: 1) a compact portion consisting of closely packed dopaminergic neurons filled with neuromelanin pigment. These neurons project to the striatum & are the ones damaged in Parkinson disease; 2) a reticular portion consisting of loosely packed neurons that receive input from the striatum and project to the thalamus.

item.label: Cerebral crus
item.name: Cerebral crus
item.description: The cerebral crus is AKA the crus cerebri or the basis pedunculi. This most ventral or inferior aspect of the paired cerebral peduncles contains motor axons originating primarily in the cerebral cortex. The bulk of the cerebral crus is made up of the corticospinal, corticobulbar and corticopontine tract fibers that have left the cerebral cortex, traveled through the internal capsule and will terminate in the spinal cord and brain stem.

item.label: Corticobulbar tract
item.name: Corticobulbar tract
item.description: The corticobulbar tract is a descending pathway (of Upper Motor Neurons) that originates in the cerebral cortex, travels through the posterior limb of the internal capsule, basis pedunculi of the midbrain, basilar pons and the pyramid of the medulla. Along its path through the brain stem it terminates or synapes (bilaterally in most, but not all, cases) on both motor and sensory nuclei. Since clinically it generally refers to only those fibers ending on motor nuclei (Lower Motor Neurons), it is considered the brainstem counterpart of the Corticospinal tract which follows the same course but terminates in the spinal cord.

item.label: Corticopontine tract
item.name: Corticopontine tract
item.description: The corticopontine tract is a descending pathway that originates in the cerebral cortex, travels through the posterior limb of the internal capsule, basis pedunculi of the midbrain and into the basilar pons where it terminates on pontine nuclei.

item.label: Corticospinal tract
item.name: Corticospinal tract
item.description: The corticospinal tract is a descending pathway (of Upper Motor Neurons) that originates in the cerebral cortex, travels through the posterior limb of the internal capsule, basis pedunculi of the midbrain, basilar pons, the pyramid of the medulla and then decussates at the medulla/spinal cord junction. Upon entering the spinal cord, the majority of the tract travels in the lateral funiculus of the spinal cord with its fibers terminating along the length of the cord on both motor and sensory neurons. Its fibers and their cells of origin are considered to be Upper Motor Neurons. This is the primary pathway that deals with skilled voluntary movements.

item.label: Interpeduncular fossa
item.name: Interpeduncular fossa
item.description: The interpeduncular fossa is the space between the cerebral peduncles on the ventral surface of the midbrain.

item.label: Interpeduncular nucleus
item.name: Interpeduncular nucleus
item.description: The interpeduncular nucleus is located medially in the ventral aspect of the caudal midbrain, between the cerebral peduncles.  It receives input from the habenula, the medial mammillary nucleus and the central superior nucleus of the raphe.  It sends output to the dorsal tegmental nucleus.

item.label: Oculomotor nerve
item.name: Oculomotor nerve
item.description: The third or oculomotor cranial nerve provides motor innervation to the ipsilateral medial rectus, superior rectus, inferior rectus, inferior oblique and levator palapebrae muscles that move the eye. It also includes parasympathetic fibers that terminate in the ipsilateral ciliary ganglion; post-ganglionic fibers from the ciliary ganglion innervate the constrictors of the pupil and the ciliary muscles.

item.label: Oculomotor nucleus
item.name: Oculomotor nuclei
item.description: This third or oculomotor cranial nerve nucleus is located in the midline of the midbrain at the level of the superior colliculi. It consists of lower motor neurons that innervate the medial rectus, superior rectus, inferior rectus, inferior oblique and levator palpebrae muscles that move the eye. It also contains pre-ganglionic parasympathetic neurons in a part of the nuclear complex called the Edinger-Westphal nucleus. These parasympathetic fibers terminate in the ciliary ganglion; post-ganglionic fibers from the ciliary ganglion innervate the constrictors of the pupil and the ciliary muscles.

item.label: Superior cistern
item.name: Quadrigeminal cistern
item.description: The superior cistern is AKA the quadrigeminal cistern or the cistern of the great cerebral vein. It is subarachnoid space located above the midbrain that is continuous with the transverse fissure. It is an important radiologic landmark since the pineal gland can be visualized within its midline location.

item.label: Internal cerebral veins
item.name: Internal cerebral veins
item.description: The internal cerebral vein is the major deep vein from each cerebral hemisphere.  It is formed at the point of the interventricular foramen by the confluence of the thalamostriate (terminal) vein and the choroidal vein.  After the confluence, the vein turns sharply posteriorly, travels in the transverse fissure and fuses with its contralateral counterpart in the superior or quadrigeminal cistern to form the Great vein of Galen.

item.label: Ventricular system
item.name: Ventricular system
item.description: The ventricular system is a series of interconnected cerebrospinal-filled chambers within the cerebral hemispheres. Cerebrospinal fluid is formed in the choroid plexus located in the lateral, third and fourth ventricles.

item.label: Lateral ventricle
item.name: Lateral ventricle
item.description: The lateral ventricle is a large, C-shaped space within each cerebral hemisphere that is filled with cerebrospinal fluid. It consists of an anterior (or frontal) horn that extends into the frontal lobe, a body, a posterior (or occipital) horn that extends into the occipital lobe, an inferior (or temporal) horn that extends into the temporal lobe and the atrium or trigone where the body, posterior limb and inferior limb meet.

item.label: Third ventricle
item.name: Third ventricle
item.description: The third ventricle is a single, narrow, vertically-oriented portion of the ventricular system.  It is located between the two halves of the thalamus and hypothalamus.

item.label: Choroid plexus
item.name: Choroid plexus
item.description: The choroid plexus is the convoluted and highly vascularized structure in the ventricles that is responsible for the production of cerebrospinal fluid.  It is located in the floor of the lateral ventricle as it curves from the body of the ventricle into the inferior horn; it is not present in the anterior or posterior horns of the lateral ventricle.  From the lateral ventricle, the choroid plexus extends through the interventricular foramina of Monro onto the roof of the third ventricle.  In the fourth ventricle the choroid plexus extends downward from the inferior medullary velum that forms part of the roof the ventricle.  The choroid plexus also extends from the fourth ventricle through the foramina of Luschka into the subarachnoid space.

item.label: Cerebral aqueduct
item.name: Cerebral aqueduct
item.description: The cerebral aqueduct is AKA the cerebral aqueduct of Sylvius.  It is a narrow channel within the midbrain through which cerebrospinal fluid flows from the third ventricle into the fourth ventricle.
